Dashboard Generation Overview

When you run main.py, the script automatically generates a Splunk dashboard definition in XML format.

The generated file is stored in the project directory as dashboard.xml.
This file can then be uploaded/imported into Splunk to visualize the syslog data.

Generated Dashboard XML

Below is the generated dashboard XML content:

<dashboard version="1.1">
  <label>AI Generated Syslog Dashboard</label>

  <row>
    <panel>
      <chart>
        <title>Events over Time</title>
        <search>
          <query>index=main sourcetype=syslog | timechart count</query>
        </search>
        <option name="charting.chart">line</option>
      </chart>
    </panel>
  </row>

  <row>
    <panel>
      <table>
        <title>Raw Events (Latest 20)</title>
        <search>
          <query>index=main sourcetype=syslog | head 20</query>
        </search>
      </table>
    </panel>
  </row>

  <row>
    <panel>
      <chart>
        <title>Top Processes</title>
        <search>
          <query>index=main sourcetype=syslog | top process</query>
        </search>
        <option name="charting.chart">bar</option>
      </chart>
    </panel>
    <panel>
      <chart>
        <title>Frequent Messages</title>
        <search>
          <query>index=main sourcetype=syslog | top message</query>
        </search>
        <option name="charting.chart">bar</option>
      </chart>
    </panel>
  </row>

</dashboard>

How It Works

Run the script:

python3 main.py


The script generates the dashboard file:

dashboard.xml


You can import dashboard.xml into Splunk via:

Splunk Web → Dashboards → Create New → Import XML

Or by placing it directly into the $SPLUNK_HOME/etc/apps/<your_app>/local/data/ui/views/ directory.

✅ After importing, you’ll see panels for:

Events over Time (line chart)

Latest Raw Events (table)

Top Processes (bar chart)

Frequent Messages (bar chart)
